            {
              "@id": "urn:uuid:9108c2fc-5aba-55e3-a69f-cadd032653ee",
              "@type": "uco-observable:ExtractedString",
              "uco-observable:stringValue": "JOHN E. KUHN, JR.\nUnited States Attorney\n\nJENNIFER IVERS\nMICHAEL EBELL\nAssistant U.S. Attorneys\nFederal Building & U.S. Courthouse\n222 West Seventh Avenue, #9, Room 253\nAnchorage, AK 99513-7567\nPhone: (907) 271-5071\nFax: (907) 271-1500\nEmail: jennifer.ivers@usdoj.gov\nEmail: michael.ebell@usdoj.gov\n\nAttorneys for Plaintiff\n\nIN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT\n\nFOR THE DISTRICT OF ALASKA\n\nUNITED STATES OF AMERICA,\n\nPlaintiff,\n\nvs. No. 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nJAYSHON MOORE, a/k/a \u201cChina,\u201d\n\nDefendant.\n\nGOVERNMENT TRIAL BRIEF\n\nCOMES NOW the United States of America, by and through the undersigned\n\ncounsel, and hereby submits this Trial Brief.\n\nI. STATUS OF THE CASE\n\nTrial in this case is set to begin before United States District Judge Sharon L.\n\nGleason on Monday, April 4, 2022, at 8:30 a.m., in Courtroom 3 at Anchorage, Alaska.\n\nAfter one full day for jury selection, the United States\u2019 presentation of evidence is\n\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 1 of 22\nexpected to last approximately three days.\n\nII. FACTUAL BACKGROUND 1\n\na. The Defendant\u2019s Background\n\nDefendant Jayshon Moore has three prior felony convictions in Alaska. Moore\u2019s\n\nmost recent conviction was in December 2010, when he was convicted of Felon in\n\nPossession and Distribution of a Controlled Substance, and Judge Burgess sentenced him\n\nto 87 months\u2019 imprisonment followed by three years of supervised release. United States\n\nv. Jayshon Moore, 3:10-cr-00044-TMB, Doc. 66. After several months in a Residential\n\nReentry Center, Moore began supervised release in October 2017. United States v.\n\nJayshon Moore, 3:10-cr-00044-TMB, Doc. 79 at 4.\n\nb. The Defendant\u2019s Production and Possession of Child Pornography\n\nNot long after his release from prison, Moore began having sexual encounters with\n\n15-year-old V.P. Those encounters are documented on V.P.\u2019s Snapchat account, obtained\n\nby law enforcement in 2019 (V.P. did not turn 18 until 2020). In 13 videos dated April\n\n28, 2019, Moore filmed V.P. performing oral sex on him. In a continuation of the same\n\nseries from the same date and time, V.P. filmed Moore as he applied lube and then had\n\nintercourse with her. Moore instructed V.P. how to arch her back and moan in the video.\n\nIn series of two videos and one photo dated May 2, 2018, Moore filmed V.P.\u2019s\n\ngenitalia while she covered her face and breasts. In a series of five videos dated May 6,\n\n1\nThe following is a brief summary of the facts of the case and is not intended to describe all of\nthe evidence the United States may offer at trial.\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 2 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 2 of 22\n2018, Moore once again filmed V.P. performing oral sex on him. Many other videos\n\nobtained from V.P.\u2019s Snapchat account depict sexual encounters between Moore and V.P.\n\nwith Moore\u2019s face clearly visible.\n\nMoore\u2019s own Snapchat account, jayinglez80, also included two videos of child\n\npornography \u2013 one of the above-listed May 6, 2018 oral sex videos that was sent to\n\nMoore on January 7, 2019, and a video of V.P. masturbating that was sent to Moore on\n\nDecember 25, 2018. Moore\u2019s response to receiving the latter video was \u201cWow.\u201d Moore\n\nappears to have used his account primarily to communicate with V.P., and their chats\n\ninclude many messages back and forth as well as many photos of them together,\n\nincluding photos of Moore holding a gun while hugging V.P.\n\nc. The Defendant\u2019s Sex Trafficking of V.P.\n\nMoore also began sex trafficking V.P. while she was 15. He set V.P\u2019s prices,\n\narranged dates, drove her to dates, and took the money she earned. In around March\n\n2019, Moore\u2019s adult girlfriend, Krista Callan, moved out of their shared apartment on\n\nMayfair Drive in Anchorage. Moore invited V.P. to move in, but only if she \u201cho\u2019ed\u201d for\n\nhim. Moore set V.P. a quota correlating to their rent. When V.P. was too tired to do dates,\n\nMoore gave her methamphetamine to wake her up. If she resisted, Moore forced V.P. to\n\nwalk in very high heels on a strip in Spenard known for street prostitution.\n\nMoore used other kinds of force to further his sex trafficking. Moore possessed\n\nguns in the residence, and he assaulted V.P. multiple times, including slamming her head\n\ninto the corner of a wall and throwing her down the stairs. At one point while V.P. was\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 3 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 3 of 22\nstill 15, she became pregnant with Moore\u2019s child. Moore forced V.P. to have an abortion\n\nbecause he knew her age and did not want to get in trouble. This is corroborated by\n\nV.P.\u2019s Snapchat posts which include a picture of a positive pregnancy test, a video of her\n\npurchasing baby supplies, a selfie saying she is excited for Moore to become a father, and\n\na final message saying they decided to have an abortion instead.\n\nd. Arrests of Defendant and V.P.\n\nMeanwhile, Moore repeatedly violated supervised release by failing to report for\n\ndrug tests, changing residences and getting fired without notifying his probation officer,\n\nand testing positive for cocaine. United States v. Jayshon Moore, 3:10-cr-00044-TMB,\n\nDocs. 94, 107. In June 2019, both V.P. and Moore were arrested \u2013 V.P. for breaking\n\nthings at their shared apartment, and Moore for violating supervised release. See United\n\nStates v. Jayshon Moore, 3:10-cr-00044-TMB, Doc. 113. Moore was sentenced to 45\n\ndays of imprisonment for those violations. United States v. Jayshon Moore, 3:10-cr-\n\n00044-TMB, Doc. 119.\n\nAfter Moore\u2019s arrest, law enforcement executed a search warrant at his residence\n\nand found V.P.\u2019s clothing, condoms and lube, and a notebook outlining prices for dates.\n\nBecause Moore had been in custody for several days before the warrant was executed,\n\nMoore\u2019s associates were removing items from the apartment and were actively doing so\n\nwhen law enforcement arrived to execute the search.\n\nLaw enforcement later obtained V.P.\u2019s online prostitution ads from\n\nskipthegames.com, which included photos taken at Moore\u2019s residence. Those ads were\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 4 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 4 of 22\nassociated to Moore\u2019s phone number, and two of them were accessed using Moore\u2019s\n\nneighbor\u2019s WiFi.\n\ne. Defendant\u2019s Statements to Law Enforcement\n\nIn January and February 2020 interviews with law enforcement, Moore admitted\n\nknowing V.P. was underage and that V.P. \u201cprobably could have\u201d sent him videos via\n\nSnapchat. Moore stated he did not have WiFi at his residence but volunteered that his\n\nneighbors probably did. During the interviews, Moore used terms like \u201cturning dates,\u201d\n\n\u201cturning tricks,\u201d \u201cin calls,\u201d \u201cturned out,\u201d and \u201cselling pussy,\u201d while denying any\n\nknowledge of sex trafficking.\n\nf. Indictment\n\nA grand jury indicted Moore on February 24, 2020 for Production of Child\n\nPornography, Possession of Child Pornography, and Sex Trafficking of a Minor. Doc. 2.\n\nAt the time, Moore was serving a five-month term of imprisonment for additional\n\nsupervised release violations. United States v. Jayshon Moore, 3:10-cr-00044-TMB,\n\nDocs. 142, 144. He has been detained pending trial. Doc. 29. The parties have filed\n\nvarious motions in limine in advance of trial that have all been addressed by this Court.\n\nIII. CHARGES AGAINST THE DEFENDANT AND LEGAL ANALYSIS\n\na. The Elements of the Charged Offenses\n\nThe United States will file separately a proposed set of instructions detailing the\n\nelements of the offenses, as well as any additional instructions for this case.\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 5 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 5 of 22\nb. Means and Facility of Interstate or Foreign Commerce\n\nThe parties intend to enter the following stipulations:\n\n1. The use of the Internet to post online prostitution advertisements on\nSkipthegames.com is in and affecting interstate and foreign\ncommerce.\n\n2. The Internet-based application Snapchat transports images and\nvideos in and affecting interstate commerce and transmits images\nand videos using any means and facility of interstate and foreign\ncommerce.\n\nThese stipulations should satisfy the interstate nexus elements of all three counts. See\n\nUnited States v. Todd, 627 F.3d 329, 333 (9th Cir. 2010) (\u201cadvertising across state\n\nlines . . . affected interstate commerce\u201d); see United States v. Grybowicz, 747 F.3d 1296,\n\n1306 (11th Cir. 2014) (\u201cThe interstate commerce element for each offense is satisfied by\n\nproof that the child pornography was transmitted using a facility of interstate or foreign\n\ncommerce, including by computer, or was produced using materials that had been\n\ntransported in interstate or foreign commerce.\u201d). Additionally, the photos and videos\n\nwere produced using smart phones manufactured outside of Alaska, which also satisfies\n\nthe interstate commerce element. Grybowicz, 747 F.3d at 1306.\n\nc. Definition of \u201cUse\u201d and \u201cEmploy\u201d\n\nAs described above, Moore himself took many pornographic pictures and videos\n\nof V.P., which constitutes using or employing V.P. to engage in sexually explicit conduct\n\nfor the purpose of producing a visual image. 18 U.S.C. 2251(a). United States v. Laursen,\n\n847 F.3d 1026, 1032-33 (9th Cir. 2017); United States v. Theis, 853 F.3d 1178, 1182\n\n(10th Cir. 2017). Photographs taken by the minor at the defendant\u2019s urging also satisfy\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 6 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 6 of 22\nthis element. Laursen, 847 F.3d at 1032.\n\nHere, even the photographs and videos taken by V.P. without Moore\u2019s instruction\n\ndepict V.P. and Moore engaging in sexually explicit conduct together, and Moore is\n\nclearly aware that he is being filmed. The United States submits that, based on the plain\n\nlanguage of the statute, Moore also used and employed V.P. to produce child\n\npornography for those videos. See United States v. Daniels, 653 F.3d 399, 408 (no\n\nrequirement that defendant took picture); cf. United States v. Broxmeyer, 616 F.3d 120\n\n(2d Cir. 2010) (holding that the government presented insufficient evidence that the\n\ndefendant persuaded, induced or enticed a 17-year-old girl to engage in sexually explicit\n\nconduct for the purpose of producing a visual depiction thereof where the victim took\n\npictures of herself and sent them to the defendant via text at some later date).\n\nThe United States intends to provide special verdict forms that distinguish\n\nbetween images that Moore took, that he directed V.P. to take, and that V.P. took\n\nincluding Moore and with his knowledge.\n\nd. Knowledge of the Victim\u2019s Age\n\nThe United States is not required to show the defendant knew a minor\u2019s age as it\n\nrelates to the charges of production or possession of child pornography. See United\n\nStates v. U.S. Dist. Court for Cent. Dist. of Cal., L.A. (Kantor), 858 F.2d 534, 538 (9th\n\nCir. 1988) (holding that \u201cknowledge of the minor\u2019s age is not necessary for conviction\n\nunder section 2251(a).\u201d)\n\nThe Ninth Circuit has ruled that in order to save 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 2251(a) from\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 7 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 7 of 22\nviolating the First Amendment, it does contain a limited mens rea defense. Specifically,\n\n\u201c[a] defendant may avoid conviction only by showing, by clear and convincing evidence,\n\nthat he did not know, and could not reasonably have learned, that the [minor] was under\n\n18 years of age.\u201d Id. at 543. Such a standard is a high one, requiring the defendant to\n\nshow both that they did not know the minor\u2019s age, and \u201cthat despite reasonable efforts,\n\nthey were unable to ascertain the minor\u2019s actual age.\u201d United States v. Ditirro, 2018 WL\n\n4934080 (D. Nev., October 11, 2018).\n\nFor purposes of proving the affirmative defense under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 2251 to a clear\n\nand convincing standard, the mere physical appearance of the victim and the context in\n\nwhich they are found are insufficient. See United States v. Dickerson, 735 Fed.Appx. 349\n\n(9th Cir. 2018) (unpublished).\n\nThe facts of Kantor demonstrate the high bar that must be met to establish the\n\naffirmative defense. In Kantor, producers of an adult film employed a physically-mature\n\n16-year-old who the producers claimed \u201cused California photographic identification,\n\nother official documents, release forms and statements of her agent and others to\n\nmisrepresent her age,\u201d and who had previously been featured in adult magazines and\n\nother adult films. Kantor, 858 F.2d at 540. The Ninth Circuit went on to describes the\n\nsteps taken by the producers to confirm the 16-year-old\u2019s age as \u201celaborate.\u201d Id.\n\nContrast the facts of Kantor with those of Dickerson, in which the Ninth Circuit\n\ndetermined that the affirmative defense had not been shown. In Dickerson, the victim told\n\nothers her true age, her true age was known to others, and the defendant failed to take any\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 8 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 8 of 22\nsteps to inquire about the victim\u2019s age. Id. at 349-50 (\u201cDickerson presented evidence that\n\nCM sometimes lied about her age, but she told his friend D\u2019Antoine Thomas that she was\n\n17; had Dickerson asked her age and received the same answer, he would still have\n\nknown she was underage.\u201d). Accordingly, Moore carries a high burden if he intends to\n\nmake a mistake of age defense for Counts 1 and 2.\n\nFor sex trafficking charged in Count 3, the standard is different. The United States\n\nmust prove that the defendant either knew or recklessly disregarded V.P.\u2019s age or had a\n\nreasonable opportunity to observe her. 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1591(a)(1), (b)(2); United States v.\n\nRobinson, 702 F.3d 22, 32 (2d Cir. 2012) (affirming statute\u2019s constitutionality); United\n\nStates v. Bolds, 620 Fed. Appx. 592, 593 (9th Cir. 2015) (citing Robinson and affirming\n\nthat \u201creasonable opportunity to observe\u201d is legal standard).\n\ne. Force, Fraud, and Coercion\n\nThe United States has alleged that not only did Moore know V.P.\u2019s age, but he\n\nalso recklessly disregarded the fact that force, fraud, or coercion would be used to cause\n\nV.P. to engage in commercial sex acts. To convict Moore on Count 3, the jury can find\n\nthat the age element of \u00a7 1591 is satisfied, or the force element, or both. As to force, there\n\nis no requirement to show actual force by the defendant or anyone else: the law requires\n\nonly that \u201cif things go as he has planned, force, fraud, or coercion will be employed to\n\ncause his victim to engage in a commercial sex transaction.\u201d Todd, 627 F.3d at 334.\n\nAs to definitions of those terms, the statute defines coercion. 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1591(e).\n\nThe United States has proposed definitions for force and fraud that were used in a recent\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 9 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 9 of 22\ntrial and are consistent with relevant caselaw. Force and fraud can include acts like\n\nphysical assault and using a victims\u2019 needs for housing, drugs, and food to cause them to\n\nengage in commercial sex acts. United States v. Lacy, 904 F.3d 889, 895 (10th Cir.\n\n2018); United States v. Carson, 870 F.3d 584, 594 (7th Cir. 2017); United States v.\n\nMcMillian, 777 F.3d 444, 447 (7th Cir. 2015); United States v. Mack, 808 F.3d 1074,\n\n1082-83 (6th Cir. 2015). Enticing victims \u201cwith promises of lucrative employment, in\n\nwhich the women could decide whether to [work], and then misappropriating their\n\nearnings while forcing them to [work]\u201d is another type of fraud. United States v. Bazar,\n\n747 Fed.Appx. 454, 457 (9th Cir. 2018); see also United States v. Smith, 719 F.3d 1120,\n\n1125 (9th Cir. 2013) (citing dictionary definition of fraud). The United States intends to\n\nintroduce evidence that Moore used physical violence, methamphetamine, the threat of\n\nthe humiliation and pain of walking the streets of Spenard, and the threat of homelessness\n\nto cause V.P. to engage in commercial sex acts and give him all or part of her earnings.\n\nf. No Requirement to Show Commercial Sex Acts Occurred\n\nAs it relates to the sex trafficking charges, the United States anticipates that\n\nevidence will show that the defendant recruited V.P. to engage in commercial sex acts\n\nand that those acts did occur. However, the criminal liability under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1591 is\n\nnot predicated on evidence of a completed sex act. Rather, the statute criminalizes acts\n\ntaken with a future intent, that is, recruiting or enticing with knowledge that a minor will\n\nbe caused to engage in a commercial sex act. See United States v. Todd, 627 F.3d 329,\n\n334 (9th Cir. 2010) (\u201cThe knowledge required of the defendant [for \u00a7 1591 liability] is\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 10 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 10 of 22\nsuch that if things go as he has planned, force, fraud or coercion will be employed to\n\ncause his victim to engage in a commercial sex transaction.\u201d); see also United\n\nStates v. Mozie, 752 F.3d 1271, 1286 (11th Cir. 2014) (\u201cIt is enough [for \u00a7 1591 liability]\n\nthat [the defendant] \u2018recruited\u2019 the victims ... to engage in commercial sex acts even\n\nthough they did not actually do so.\u201d); United States v. Jungers, 702 F.3d 1066, 1073 (8th\n\nCir. 2013) (\u201cIn many, if not all cases, the commercial sex act is still in the future at the\n\ntime the purchaser ... [is] in violation of \u00a7 1591.\u201d) This conclusion - that the intended\n\ntrafficking need not be satisfied for liability to attach - is confirmed in part by the\n\ndefinition of \u201cvictim of trafficking\u201d in a related statute as, among other things, a person\n\nwho has been \u201charbor[ed] [or] obtain[ed] ... for the purpose of a commercial sex act.\u201d 22\n\nU.S.C. \u00a7 7102(10). It is therefore irrelevant to the analysis of guilt if an act of commercial\n\nsex is actually proven.\n\nIV. GOVERNMENT\u2019S CASE IN CHIEF\n\nThe government anticipates calling the following witnesses in its case-in-chief.\n\nPlease note that the government has not yet determined the final order in which the\n\nwitnesses will testify. In addition, this following list is not dispositive, and the United\n\nStates reserves the right to amend or supplement the witnesses it intends to call at trial:\n\na. FBI SSA James Hardie 2\n\nFBI Supervisory Special Agent James Hardie is a special agent with specific\n\n2\nThe United States filed a Notice of Expert with a more comprehensive summary of SSA\nHardie\u2019s testimony at Docket 96.\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 11 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 11 of 22\ntraining and experience relating to sex trafficking. He will provide expert testimony about\n\nthe dynamics of sex trafficking, the relationship between traffickers and their victims, and\n\nthe commercial sexual exploitation of children. SSA Hardie will testify about how\n\ntraffickers identify and groom their victims, the methods they use to ensure their victims\n\ncontinue engaging in prostitution, and how victims may respond to law enforcement. He\n\nwill further testify about how victims may provide conflicting or incomplete descriptions\n\nof their trafficking, often because of fear or affection for their trafficker. SSA Hardie will\n\ntestify about how traffickers use romance to entice victims and ensure their loyalty. He\n\nwill testify about terms that the government has good cause to believe will be introduced\n\nthrough other witnesses and evidence in this case, such as \u201cin-call,\u201d \u201cout-call,\u201d \u201cfull-\n\nhour,\u201d \u201chalf-hour,\u201d \u201cquick visit,\u201d \u201cdozen roses,\u201d \u201cdate,\u201d \u201cbottom,\u201d and \u201cwife.\u201d See Doc.\n\n154.\n\nb. FBI SA Lisa Watson\n\nSA Lisa Watson is the case agent and will provide background information about\n\nthe investigation. She will testify that FBI obtained Snapchat search warrants for V.P. and\n\nMoore\u2019s accounts and will describe the evidence found in those accounts. 3 SA Lisa\n\nWatson will testify about V.P.\u2019s approximate age in the child pornography pictures and\n\nvideos, based on the dates provided by Snapchat and the date they were obtained by FBI.\n\nShe will describe the sexually explicit nature of those pictures and videos. SA Lisa\n\n3\nThis Court has granted the government\u2019s motion in limine to allow authentication of the\nSnapchat accounts under Rule 902. Doc. 116.\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 12 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 12 of 22\nWatson will also testify about information obtained by the government from Skip the\n\nGames, including advertisements depicting V.P. and the phone numbers and IP addresses\n\nassociated with those ads. She will testify what Skip the Games is. She will explain that\n\ninformation provided by GCI indicates that at least two of the ads were posted using\n\nWiFi belonging to Moore\u2019s neighbor. SA Lisa Watson will testify that photos from V.P.\u2019s\n\nads match features of Moore\u2019s residence, and she will testify about FBI\u2019s unsuccessful\n\nefforts to obtain Moore\u2019s phone.\n\nc. V.P.\n\nV.P. will testify that she met Moore through her sister when she was 14 or 15\n\nyears old. Moore knew V.P. was a minor because she and others told him. V.P. will\n\nconfirm that Moore took many of the photos and videos of her engaging in sexually\n\nexplicit conduct with him. She will explain that when she asked to move in with Moore at\n\nhis Mayfair residence in April 2019, Moore told her that she had to engage in commercial\n\nsex acts if she wanted to live with him. V.P. will testify that Moore told her to post on\n\nSkiptheGames.com, which she did, and she will identify those posts. She will testify that\n\nboth she and Moore communicated with clients, that some of the dates occurred at\n\nMoore\u2019s residence, and that he drove her to others. V.P. will testify that Moore set her\n\nprices and took most of the money she made from dates. Moore set her a quota that\n\ncorrelated with the rent for their apartment. She will say that when she wanted to stop\n\ndoing commercial sex acts, Moore got upset with her and punished her by making her\n\nwear high heels and walk Spenard. Moore also gave her methamphetamine to wake her\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 13 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 13 of 22\nup to go on more dates. V.P. will testify that Moore physically assaulted her on multiple\n\noccasions and that he often carried a gun. V.P. will say that Moore asked her to bring him\n\nanother minor after seeing a picture of the minor on V.P.\u2019s phone, but the other minor\n\ndidn\u2019t like the situation and never came back.\n\nd. Krista Callan\n\nKrista Callan will testify that she was Moore\u2019s long-term girlfriend until he\n\ncheated on her with V.P. She will explain that she confronted Moore about V.P.\u2019s age.\n\nCallan will testify that she moved out of the Mayfair residence around March 2019, and\n\nMoore continued to live there. She was present when a search warrant was executed at\n\nthat residence in June 2019, after she had moved out.\n\ne. Marquita Patterson\n\nMarquita Patterson will testify that Moore and V.P. met through her and that she\n\ntold Moore multiple times how young V.P. was.\n\nf. FBI SA Michael Watson\n\nSA Michael Watson will testify about the search of the Mayfair residence in June\n\n2019. He will testify about the photos taken and the physical evidence seized.\n\ng. US Coast Guard SA Adam Carron\n\nSA Carron will testify about the search of an Escalade used by Moore on the same\n\nday as the search of the Mayfair residence and the recovery of a red notebook containing\n\ninformation about prices for commercial sex acts.\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 14 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 14 of 22\nh. Christina Schmitt\n\nChristina Schmitt will testify that she was Moore\u2019s neighbor at the Mayfair\n\nresidence before and after Callan moved out. She will testify that she saw Moore with\n\nV.P., and she saw many men and women coming and going from the apartment,\n\nespecially after Callan moved out. One night she believed she heard a woman screaming\n\nand being pushed into a wall, and another night she saw Moore with six or seven\n\nscantily-clad women coming out of the apartment.\n\ni. FBI Task Force Officer (TFO) Torres\n\nTFO Torres will testify about his interview of the defendant, as well as jail calls\n\nmade to and from the defendant. He will testify about the dates of his interviews with\n\nV.P., and if needed will impeach V.P.\u2019s testimony about those interviews.\n\nV. EVIDENTIARY AND LEGAL ISSUES\n\na. Authentication of Jail Calls\n\nThe United States intends to introduce recorded jail calls to and from the\n\ndefendant. The government and the defendant will stipulate to the authenticity of those\n\ncalls, allowing them to be introduced without discussion of the defendant or his\n\nassociates being in custody.\n\nb. Prior Inconsistent Statements by V.P.\n\nThe parties discussed at the final pretrial conference whether SSA Hardie should\n\nbe permitted to testify about potential inconsistent statements by victims, given that\n\nMoore may choose not to impeach V.P. with those statements. The United States submits\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 15 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 15 of 22\nthat it has a good faith belief that V.P. will need to be impeached with prior inconsistent\n\nstatements during her direct examination, making SSA Hardie\u2019s testimony relevant.\n\nc. Testimony About Abortion\n\nHaving reviewed this Court\u2019s order at Docket 160, the United States submits that\n\nthere is additional evidence of Moore\u2019s role in V.P.\u2019s 2018 abortion. V.P.\u2019s Snapchat\n\naccount contains images of positive pregnancy tests, videos of her buying baby supplies,\n\na photo of herself with a caption that she is pregnant and is excited for her husband\n\n(Moore) to become a father, and a subsequent photo saying that she was going to Planned\n\nParenthood to get an abortion because they decided not to keep it. The United States\n\nsubmits that with this additional evidence, it has met its burden under Rule 403, and the\n\ntestimony is relevant to Moore\u2019s power and control over V.P., as well as his knowledge\n\nof her age.\n\nIf not admissible in the government\u2019s case in chief, this evidence will become\n\nrelevant if Moore, in opening statement, cross examination, or testimony, denies having\n\nsexual intercourse with V.P., denies knowing that she was 15 when he did so, or disputes\n\nhaving power over V.P.\u2019s important life decisions. The Snapchat evidence makes it clear\n\nthat V.P. wanted to have a child and that Moore influenced the decision to have an\n\nabortion instead. She will testify that Moore made that decision unilaterally to hide the\n\nfact that he was having sexual intercourse with a child. Even if this Court finds the\n\nabortion testimony too prejudicial to introduce in the government\u2019s case-in-chief, it\n\nshould allow the testimony if Moore opens the door by denying having intercourse with\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 16 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 16 of 22\nV.P., denying knowledge of her age, or denying having a role in her decision-making\n\nduring the charged time period.\n\nd. Statements by the Defendant\n\nA party may introduce the out-of-court statements of his opponent as party\n\nadmissions. Fed. R. Evid. 801(d)(2); United States v. Romo-Chavez, 681 F.3d 955, 959\n\n(9th Cir. 2012). The United States intends to introduce statements made by the defendant\n\nduring the course of his criminal conduct, either to witnesses in this case, as part of\n\nSnapchat messages with V.P., or to others that were captured in audio recordings.\n\nAdmissions by a party-opponent are treated as non-hearsay under Rule\n\n801(d)(2)(A) and are thus admissible for their truth. Under the Federal Rules of\n\nEvidence, a defendant\u2019s statement is admissible only if offered against him; the defendant\n\nmay not elicit his own prior statements. Fed. R. Evid. 801(d)(2)(A); United States v.\n\nFernandez, 839 F.2d 639 (9th Cir. 1988). Neither the 6th Amendment right to\n\nconfrontation nor the Rule of Completeness under Fed. R. Evid. 106 compel a different\n\nresult. See United States v. Collicott, 92 F.3d 973, 983 (9th Cir.1996) (finding that \u201crule\n\n106 \u2018does not compel admission of otherwise inadmissible hearsay evidence\u2019\u201d) (quoting\n\nPhoenix Associates III v. Stone, 60 F.3d 95, 103 (2d Cir.1995)).\n\nIn some instances, the defendant\u2019s statements will be introduced as part of a larger\n\nconversation between him and another person. For instance, the defendant\u2019s Snapchat\n\nmessages with V.P. contain back and forth communications between the two. His\n\nstatements to law enforcement sometimes include a questions or assertion by the\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 17 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 17 of 22\nindividual speaking to the defendant, followed by an answer, affirmation, or denial by the\n\ndefendant.\n\nThese statements by V.P. and others are admissible when they provide \u201ccontext\n\nfor other admissible statements [and] are not hearsay because they are not offered for\n\ntheir truth.\u201d United States v. Tolliver, 454 F.3d 660, 666 (7th Cir. 2006); see also United\n\nStates v. Payne, 944 F.2d 1458, 1472 (9th Cir. 1991) (finding out-of-court statements to a\n\nvictim questioning whether she had been sexually abused were non-hearsay because they\n\nwere offered to show their effect on the victim and to explain the circumstances under\n\nwhich her initial denial of molestation by the defendant took place); United States v.\n\nBermea-Boone, 563 F.3d 621, 626 (7th Cir. 2009) (affirming that it is \u201cwell-settled\u201d that\n\nstatements that are offered for context and not for the truth of the matter asserted, are not\n\nhearsay, and do not present a Crawford issue).\n\ne. Defense Exhibits\n\nUnder this Court\u2019s order at Docket 83, counsel for Moore sent the United States a\n\nlist of proposed audio and video exhibits, including: two videos of V.P.; video and stills\n\nfrom Moore\u2019s apartment after V.P.\u2019s arrest in June 2019; Snapchat \u201craw data\u201d; 8 pages of\n\nMoore\u2019s Bureau of Prison records; and Moore\u2019s employment records. The United States\n\nmay object to admission of some or all of those exhibits.\n\nThe two videos of V.P. show V.P. in what appears to be a fit of rage. In one of the\n\nvideos, V.P. appears to throw a stick or short pole at Moore\u2019s Cadillac Escalade. The\n\nproffered video is inadmissible character evidence. United States v. Noti, 731 F.2d 610,\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 18 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 18 of 22\n612-13 (9th Cir. 1984) (citing Fed. R. Evid. 404(a) & 608(b)) (character evidence is\n\ngenerally inadmissible, and \u201c[e]vidence of a witness\u2019 past misconduct, other than\n\nconviction of a crime, is inadmissible for the purpose of attacking the witness\u2019\n\ncredibility.\u201d).\n\nIn the other video, V.P. yells at Moore that he is going to jail because of his \u201cankle\n\nmonitor\u201d and because of the \u201cvideos.\u201d Moore presumably seeks to introduce this video as\n\nevidence of V.P.\u2019s \u201cmental problems and [] grudge against the defendant.\u201d Doc. 140 at 1.\n\nIf the video showed V.P.\u2019s bias toward Moore, it could be admissible. Id. at 613 (\u201cEvidence\n\nthat happens to include prior misconduct may be admissible, however, when it is offered\n\nto show the witness\u2019 possible bias or self-interest in testifying.\u201d (citing Burr v. Sullivan,\n\n618 F.2d 583, 586\u201387 (9th Cir. 1980)). This video, however, does not show bias by V.P.,\n\nbut instead was a truthful assessment of the defendant\u2019s criminal liability for making videos\n\nof her and something to do with his ankle monitor. Regardless, admission of the video will\n\nreveal that Moore was on an ankle monitor when he committed these new offenses, causing\n\npotential prejudice. The United States will object on those grounds, and possibly others, if\n\nMoore seeks to introduce that video.\n\nVideo and stills from V.P.\u2019s arrest likewise only serve the purpose of portraying\n\nV.P. as a crazy criminal and are inadmissible. See United States v. George, 532 F.3d 933,\n\n937 (D.C. Cir. 2008) (\u201cThe days are long past when any mental illness was presumed to\n\nundermine a witness\u2019s competence to testify.\u201d) Gonzalez v. Wong, 667 F.3d 965, 983 (9th\n\nCir. 2011) (cross-examination about mental health only permissible if condition\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 19 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 19 of 22\n\u201cdramatically impair[s]\u201d their \u201cability to perceive and tell the truth.\u201d (quoting United States\n\nv. Butt, 955 F.2d 77, 82\u201383 (1st Cir.1992)).\n\nFinally, the \u201craw data\u201d from V.P. and Moore\u2019s Snapchat accounts includes a\n\nsubstantial amount of hearsay and should not be admitted in full. The government intends\n\nto admit only the relevant, non-hearsay evidence from the Snapchat accounts.\n\nVI. TRIAL LOGISTICS\n\na. Presentation of Contraband Evidence\n\nAs discussed at the final pretrial conference, the United States intends to admit\n\ncontraband videos and images without publishing them in open court. Instead, stills from\n\nthose videos will be published, along with a description of the video by the case agent.\n\nThis will minimize embarrassment of the victim and mental exhaustion of the jury.\n\nThe parties have also discussed allowing the jury to bring the contraband evidence\n\n\u2013 which will be on a separate, clearly marked disc or external hard drive \u2013 into the jury\n\nroom for deliberations. The parties have agreed that the Court should permit a limited\n\nexception to the local rules and allow this, rather than requiring the jury to return to the\n\ncourtroom to view the contraband.\n\nb. Use of Court Laptop\n\nThe United States reiterates that it does not have an extra laptop to give to the jury\n\nfor this or any other trial. FBI has provided one, however, that can be used during this\n\ntrial. Exhibits will be provided to the jury in the form of printed documents, discs, and\n\nhard drives, rather than directly loaded onto the laptop.\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 20 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 20 of 22\nc. DEPS Controls\n\nThe government\u2019s DEPS control panel power cord in Courtroom 3 is too short to\n\nreach the paralegal table at the front of the gallery. United States respectfully asks it to be\n\nextended.\n\nd. Courtroom Security\n\nThe United States is not aware of any unique security risks.\n\nVII. POSSIBLE DEFENSES\n\nThe defendant has not filed notice of any defense. If timely notice is not provided\n\nin accordance with the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, the government will seek to\n\npreclude the defendant from presenting any evidence of such a defense.\n\nVIII. WITNESS EXCLUSION AND CASE AGENT DESIGNATION\n\nUnder Federal Rule of Evidence 615, the government will seek to exclude all\n\nwitnesses until their testimony is complete. The United States moves that SA Lisa\n\nWatson be designated as the case agent and exempted from the exclusion order. 4\n\n//\n\n//\n\n//\n\n//\n\n//\n\n//\n\n4\nFed. R. Evid. 615; see also United States v. Little, 753 F.2d 1420, 1441 (9th Cir. 1985).\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 21 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 21 of 22\nRESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED March 28, 2022 at Anchorage, Alaska.\n\nJOHN E. KUHN, JR.\nUnited States Attorney\n\n/s Jennifer Ivers\nJENNIFER IVERS\nAssistant United States Attorney\nUnited States of America\n\nCERTIFICATE OF SERVICE\n\nI hereby certify that on March 28, 2022\na true and correct copy of the foregoing\nwas served electronically on:\n\nElizabeth Fleming\n\n/s Jennifer Ivers\nOffice of the U.S. Attorney\n\nU.S. v. Moore\n3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS\nPage 22 of 22\nCase 3:20-cr-00029-SLG-MMS Document 172 Filed 03/28/22 Page 22 of 22"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
